	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Gyre of FV</b><br /><i>3)  If a weapon has an innate proc and an imbued proc, both the innate and the imbued proc will occur about as often as each would if they were the only proc<br />
<br />
There does appear to be a very slight reduction in procs, as both won't go in the same swing.  But that's about, what 2% * 2% of swings?</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>It's <i>possible</i> for the following to be true, depending on how the combat system works:<br />
(a) Innate proc rate is constant whether or not there's also an imbued proc and/or augment proc.<br />
(b) Imbued proc rate is constant whether or not there's also an innate proc and/or augment proc.<br />
(c) Augment proc rate is constant whether or not there's also an innate proc and/or imbued proc.<br />
(d) Innate, imbued, and augment procs never occur on the same swing/hit.<br />
<br />
How? I suggest that the combat system uses one and only one RNG roll to determine if there is a proc or not. Let's say it's called R(proc) and has a range from 0 to 1. Each proc has it's own success range:<br />
<br />
Innate proc (success!) if 0 < R(proc) < 0.02<br />
Imbued proc (success!) if 0.1 < R(proc) < 0.12<br />
Augment proc (success!) if 0.2 < R(proc) < 0.22<br />
Etc.<br />
<br />
As a result, each proc has a 2% chance of occurring <i>and</i> two procs can't happen at the same time.<br />
<br />
Weapon procs require at least one set of server-side calculations every swing. For the purposes of streamlining the combat system, one and only one RNG roll makes sense. Stats could still easily affect proc rates - the success range could be increased from 0 < R(proc) < 0.02 to 0 < R(proc) < 0.05 based on dexterity, for example.</p>
	
	
	
